'''Nishinorikura Kofun''' (西乗鞍古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun}} Kofun located in {{ill|Tenri City|ja|天理市}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県}}, Japan. It is a keyhole-shaped Kofun (前方後円墳) and part of the {{ill|Somanouchi Kofun Group|ja|杣之内古墳群|1=Somanouchi Kofun cluster}}. The site is Historic site as a National {{ill|Historic site|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan}}} within the "Somanouchi Kofun Group."  

== Overview ==  
Nishinorikura Kofun is a large keyhole-shaped Kofun constructed at the base of a ridge extending east to west along the eastern edge of the {{ill|Nara Basin|ja|奈良盆地}}. Together with the {{ill|Higashinorikura Kofun|ja|東乗鞍古墳}} and {{ill|Obaka Kofun|ja|小墓古墳}}, it types a subgroup within the Somanouchi Kofun Group. To date, four excavation surveys have been conducted.  

The mound is oriented southward, with the front rectangular portion facing that direction. It is believed to have a two-tier construction. The mound's surface has revealed {{ill|Cylindrical haniwa|ja|円筒埴輪|1=Cylindrical Haniwa}} and {{ill|shaped haniwa|ja|形象埴輪|1=Figural Haniwa}}.<ref name="ExplanationSign"/> The mound also has projections on the eastern and western sides of the constriction area. Surrounding the mound are a moat (inner moat) and an embankment, typeing a flat area (now buried) that extends approximately 165 meters in total length from north to south.<ref name="ExplanationSign"/> An outer moat has also been identified on the southern and eastern sides, suggesting a double moat system. The burial chamber is presumed to be a {{ill|Yokoana-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber}}.<ref name="ExplanationSign"/> burial goods such as {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery}} and {{ill|Haji pottery|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery}} have also been discovered.<ref name="ExplanationSign"/>  

The construction period is estimated to be the late 5th century, near the end of the {{ill|Middle Kofun period|ja|古墳時代中期}}.<ref name="ExplanationSign">Explanation sign on-site.</ref> This mound is one of the largest from its time, second only to imperial Kofuns. Nearby, Higashinorikura Kofun and Obaka Kofun date to the early Late Kofun period, and these mounds are hypothesized to be burial sites for the leaders of the {{ill|Mononobe clan|ja|物部氏}}.<ref>{{Cite book|和書|author=Shiraishi Taichirō|chapter=The Mononobe Clan Viewed from Kofun|title=Reasoning About the Buried of Kofun (Chūkō Series)|publisher=[[Chūōkōron-shinsha]]|year=2018|pages=253-260}}</ref>  

In 2018, Nishinorikura Kofun was Historic site a National {{ill|Historic site|ja|史跡|1=Historic site|lt=Historic site of Japan}}} as part of the "Somanouchi Kofun Group."<ref name="Notification"/>  

== Mound burial ==  
The mound's area are as follows:{{Sfn|Somanouchi Kofun Group Study|2014}}{{Sfn|Nishinorikura Kofun (Tenri Kofun 100)|2015}}  
* Mound length: Approx. 118 meters  
* Rear circular portion: Possibly two-tiered  
** Diameter: Approx. 66 meters  
** Height: Approx. 15.5 meters  
* Front rectangular portion  
** Width: Approx. 88 meters  
** Height: Approx. 16 meters  

The mound length Ranks second within the Somanouchi Kofun Group, following {{ill|Nishiyama Kofun|ja|西山古墳}}. A flat area resembling a base extends approximately 20–30 meters east-west and 130 meters north-south along the western edge of the mound. Excavation suggests that this flat area resulted from the burial of the inner moat and embankment. An outer moat has also been discovered, indicating the potential presence of a double moat system.  

